<section xml:id="sec_cob_summ">
  <title>Summary</title>
  <p>
    The key ideas in this section are the coordinate vector with respect to a basis and the change of basis matrix.
    <ul>
      <li>
        <p>
          If <m>\CB = \{\vv_1, \vv_2, \vv_3, \ldots, \vv_n\}</m> is a basis for <m>\R^n</m>,
          then the coordinate vector of <m>\vx</m> with respect to <m>\CB</m> is the vector
          <me>
            [\vx]_{\CB} = [x_1 \ x_2 \ \ldots \ x_n]^{\tr}
          </me>,
          where
          <me>
            \vx = x_1 \vv_1 + x_2 \vv_2 + \cdots + x_n \vv_n
          </me>.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          If <m>\CB = \{\vb_1, \vb_2, \ldots, \vb_n\}</m> and
          <m>\CC = \{\vc_1, \vc_2, \ldots, \vc_n\}</m> are two bases for <m>\R^n</m>,
          then the change of basis matrix from <m>\CB</m> to <m>\CC</m> is the matrix
          <me>
            \underset{\CC \leftarrow \CB}{P} = [[\vb_1]_{\CC} \ [\vb_2]_{\CC}  \  \cdots  \ [\vb_n]_{\CC}]
          </me>
          that satisfies
          <me>
            [\vx]_{\CC} = \underset{\CC \leftarrow \CB}{P}[\vx]_{\CB}
          </me>
          for any vector <m>\vx</m> in <m>\R^n</m>.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          Change of basis matrices allow us to effectively and efficiently transition from one coordinate system to another.
        </p>
      </li>
    </ul>
  </p>
</section>